Sending and receiving data via sockets is not instantaneous. Method `readUTF` will wait until there is data to read. It will read all the data sent in the last invocation of method `writeUTF`. Method `readUTF` will wait indefinitely. Hence the server needs to send notification to the client that there is no more data to send. In the above code I send the string **END** to indicate the end of the data that the server is sending. Note also that you only need to close resources that you explicitly create. In class `MyServer`, this means `ServerSocket` only. I use [try-with-resources][1] to ensure that `ServerSocket` is closed.

Similarly, in class `MyClient`, the only resource that needs to be explicitly closed is the `Socket` &amp;ndash; which I again do using *try-with-resources*.

If the server terminates, the socket is closed. Hence, in class `MyServer`, after sending data to the client, the server waits for two seconds which is hopefully enough time for the client to read that data.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html

